values:
Setting: work, behind the counter with my ex about ten feet away.  

Nancy: Oh, your boyfriend.  *Nods in his direction*
Me: *glances*  Not anymore.
Nancy: What?
Me: Nope.  Whatever, it's fine.
Nancy: You not dating anymore? Why?
Me: He broke up with me.  It's fine.
*exbf approaches*
Joe: What's going on?
Me: Nothing.  She's just causing trouble.
Joe: *mimes smacking Nancy upside the head and says something I don't catch*
Nancy: *grins*
*Joe leaves*
Nancy: So, why he broke up with you?
Me: I really don't know.  *tries to look busy in case Joe comes back*
Nancy: That stupid!  You a beautiful woman, you have good education!  Why he not want you?
Me: I don't know.  *shrugs*
Nancy: What he want?  A black woman?
Me: What?! I, uh, I have no idea.
Nancy: *continues in a Chinese accent, which at this point I can't understand*
Me: *laughs because what else can I do?* Nancy, I have no idea what he wants.
Nancy: *smiles mischievously and shakes her head*

The end.

When I was about five I decided I wanted to go to Japan (I think Big Bird in Japan settled it for me, although my family has had connections to Japan independent of that).

So, in college I minored in Japanese.  I've never really had a chance to put it to use.

Here's where it gets interesting - my choir is going to tour Taiwan in a couple months, and my friends and I are planning to hop over to Japan.  

However, I'm in part-time job land, and two part times does not one full time make.  

So.  My choir is doing a fundraiser - we're selling Yankee Candles.  If any of you would like to support my dream of traveling to East Asia, please let me know before the end of the month.  Products will arrive before Easter, so they would make great Easter presents!  Or no reason at all presents.  

The cheapest items are crackly glass dragonfly votive or tea light holders for $5.  There are car refreshers for $6 and some other really nice items in the 12-20 range.  

There are funky metal ant candle holders for $5 or $6 (small and large), perfect for decorating for outdoor meals on the patio!  You can use these to display the watermelon scented tea lights ($10 for 12 candles - also in cinnamon vanilla, sugar cane & vanilla, berry crumble, and sage & cinnamon).  

They even have BBQ sauce, steak sauce and teriyaki and szechuan grilling sauce for $10 each!  in addition to these fine products, there are windchimes ($12), pet picture frames ($8), dog treats in chicken parlsey and beef parmesan ($8), plug-in scented oil ($14), glass candleholders that look like lamps ($18), hanging strawberry plants ($12), garden gloves (3 pairs for $9), a recipe box with 50 recipe cards ($16), 50 square feet of assorted gift wrap ($6), super pretty gift bags (3 for $8), and what I think is the cutest and most useful item of all, the Old Farmer's Almanac Garden Journal for $14.  They also have super-natural (haha) soaps with glycerine in lavender and wild honeysuckle (2 for $10); one comes with flower petals and the other in a pretty organza bag - a perfect gift for Mom or a sister!

And of course there are the regular large candles in jars for $21 and votive gift sets in cute baskets for $12.

So that's my spiel.  Let me know if you're interested!

Not really.  But almost!

If you recorded tonight's Law & Order (I know you didn't, but play along), and you paused at just the right moment, you would see next to a large poster a head in a furry hood.  That'd be me, shouting "1, 2, 3, 4, Barlowe is a right wing whore!"

AND!

Tonight my choir performed at the State Theatre.  We sounded pretty good.  And we wore the pretty dresses.  I hope someone gives us money for touring.

So yup, I'm as good as famous!  I just don't have to worry so much about the stalkers like really famous people.  Good deal, ne?

I have a job interview for an editing job!  Actually, I might have two.  (My resume apparently didn't attach properly when I sent it to one place, and the guy wrote back, saying he "read my email with interest" but didn't get the resume.  So, instead of assuming I don't pay attention to detail and rejecting me, he asked to see it.)  

I am quite happy.  Yay for possibilities!

So, if anyone hears anyone say anything about that women's choir that wears black pants, red shirts, and sucks, please reply with something like, "Oh, well, I guess anyone can have an off day.  I heard they're really good."

Thank you for your support.

So, I'm gonna write a list of things that either don't make sense or sound really really odd.  They will be explained at the bottom, and easily located due to the corresponding numerals.  W00t.

1) I got my toothbrush back from Jamie today.  I was really glad, 'cause I'd been without it for a few days.  I missed that just brushed feeling.

2) My friend James bought me ice cream today, which was really nice.  Of course, I kinda suggested he do it because he made my throat hurt.  And no, he didn't make me sick.  He just said something and that made my throat hurt.  So I was like, now you have to buy me frozen dessert!  And he did.  'Cause he rocks.

3) Nick and I had an interesting conversation over lunch where I explained that it was not in fact an elephant on my head, but a platypus.  And then I realized that my natural high on life was just ridiculously strong today (or something like that) and I was confused.  Because of course it wasn't Patty on my head, it was Aarty's pig.  And although I said I left a pig at Anne's apartment, I corrected myself and told him that it was actually a cow.  There are lots of cows on Cook so I bet Daisy blends right in.

4) MattLafargue just called me his booty.

***Explanations***

1) I left my travel toothbrush at Jamie's after spending the night there.  Usually it lives in my purse so I can have that minty fresh feeling during the day.

2) James said something sooo 5th grade that he knew would make me laugh.  Only I was eating, so I almost choked on lettuce with caesar dressing.  My advice is to try to avoid doing that because it does not feel nice.

3) Actually, that one makes sense.  If you know that I'm talking about a photo of me with Aarty's stuffed pig on my head.

4) Me: Hi, what's shakin'?
MattLafargue: Hi, my booty!

*Owari*

I won't go into detail about today... basically, it dragged on, but had a few high points.

I wore hot pink stockings and not only did I get a kick out of them, but so did a few of my friends (and a couple people I don't know!).  Woot for colorful clothing.

Um, I made new friends today.  After a couple weeks of exposing Maria to my crazy friends at lunch, I was introduced to a couple of hers.  They weren't so crazy, but were totally awesome!!!  I like making friends where right away you feel free to just be yourself and chat and be friendly.  They were awesome.

Also made friends with a guy I had been meaning to introduce myself to.  He signed me into Demarest the night I went to watch Life of Brian, but we didn't get much of a chance to chat.  I saw him on the porch today and said hi.  We chatted for a while and then walked to the bus stop together.  It was another of those, well we just met but we're friends already experiences that I love.  And he taught me how to shoot rubber bands, which may or may not turn out to be a good thing.  ^_^  He's artsy and cool.  Maybe he'll join the lit mag!

Speaking of which, there are lots of new members.  It roxors!  Ha ha, I'm so not even a gamer...
Have you ever noticed that the lyrics to "My Sharona" are kinda dirty?  6_6

http://www.pixyland.org/peterpan/

Well, not really.  I do think this man knows he's not teh Peter... I hope.

And I used to have a crush on Peter Pan as a kid... you know, the animated one, who was actually a boy.  And not to be shallow or anything, but I would think that Peter, were he real, might have a more flattering haircut... I mean, what kid keeps his hair all freakin perfectly curled under like that, anyway?  No, it'd be a messy look, I think.

Anyway... I'm actually spending time thinking about this.  Wow.  Um, time for homework.

But it's kinda funny how the message this dude wants to spread is that if you're weird, then God made you weird.  Hm, that's nice, but a bit broad.  For example, you could be a murderer and really like it, which is weird in my book.  He also says that modern religion has lost sight of the concept of a God who loves everyone.  I guess he's refering to how lots of churches aren't really into heretics (people who like to think for themselves, which is awesome) and weirdos (pedophiles, for example - totally not awesome).  I think the most succinct way to sum up what I think about this is to post a quote: "God loves us as we are, but (s)he loves us too much to leave us that way."  It doesn't help if you accept everything about how you currently are, cause then you'll resist changing in positive ways.  Like, stopping killing people.  

But yeah, only one thing left to say: Owari.

Yeah, so I feel better today. I saw that dude that I was sad about and I felt totally okay. So I figure I can manage and still hang out with him while these silly feelings fade away. And right now I have to finish this creative writign assignment, but the feedback I got was so general... I don't know specifically what to do. I think I need to write completely new parts to it, 'cause everyone was like, whatever happened to this character? He just disappeared! Yeah, 'cause he wasn't important to the story anymore, DUH! Losers. Not really, but why do they care? I'm sorry the story didn't go where they thought it would. Meh. And I'm not even going to try to convince anyone that this chick likes this guy... I guess her feeling all uncomfy around him and trying to mentally play it off in a "teenybopperish" way isn't real to my class. But yeah, the character is 16. And the "teenybopper" line was in italics, which means she was thinking it. You don't think she should think something that a 16 year old might think? My apologies for being realistic. Blah. If only the criticism had HELPED. Now I'm stuck like, aaargh, what do I write??? I can't really take a lot of the written comments seriously because there are instances where one person wrote "I like this!" and another wrote "this doesn't make sense" about the SAME line. Yeah. My story was heavy in details. I'm sorry television has given us all crappy attention spans, but if I had been allowed to speak, I would have been able to say, "that's actually explained on page 2, in paragraph 3." But no. Rawr. I have a feeling that I shouldn't actually be upset about this, but I'm just so tired and I think my prof is gonna be stupid and like, "this is a bit better, but I can only give you a C." Which I should not assume, of course, but based on what she said, I need to add so much and delete massive amounts of details (because of course, a character talking about himself only confuses readers. I should show, not tell. And yeah, showing is better than telling, but this is like 17 years of history I have to get through to make the present make sense! Gr). And they're so curious at the same time. I can't resolve EVERYTHING in 8 pages. I did have to bring up certain dramas and problems to make other things relevant, so I couldn't just leave them out. Yes, it would be nice to find out what happens with the brother who ran off. Maybe I'll just stay up all night and make up some big confrontational something and hand in 40 pages tomorrow. And fail, because that would be really annoying. And you know, maybe NOTHING happens with the brother who ran away except that his younger brother has to deal with his own insecurity and not drive his friend crazy (which all connects to the disappearance of the older brother, which is why I had to mention it). If I just knew what to focus on... rawr. Well, they want a simpler story, so I guess I'll just make it simpler. I can do that, but what if things make even LESS sense? Won't know until I try. And I guess I'll have to remove Chris's name from the story. Because the readers can't simply assume that he's just some random guy that the narrator knows and realize that he had to be mentioned to explain why Grey is at a certain social event. "Maybe you could just make Grey show up on his own," my teacher said. NO! Grey would not do that!!! If you were paying attention to the part where the narrator talks about Grey, you would realize that. Yes, there were a LOT of details and perhaps you missed something important, but please don't tell me that my character should be more outgoing than he is. Dammit, he's not social. Therefore, Chris brings Grey and Grey starts the narrator thinking about what he's going to tell us, part of which is things about Grey and how he's related to lots of other things that're going on. It's like one of those inventions where dropping an egg into a skillet triggers the badger to run towards the food and the rope on his tail pulls up the garage door. It makes perfect sense! You just have to follow the little diagram. You don't have to know anything about Chris!!! He doesn't matter to this story except for that one little aspect!!! Rawr. Well, here I go to edit/rewrite/make up new stuff.

Today was such a good day.

Until I got depressed.  ^_^

I just realized something in such a way that I cannot, even with all my optimism, find a way to avoid accepting.

And no, no one's dying.  It's just one of those things that's just sad enough to leave you feeling A) really really sorry for yourself, and B) generally like crap.

So Swappy and Jamie are like, let's cheer you up but they're cool enough to not try too hard.  They just pat me on the head (well, they haven't yet, but it's like that) and I almost feel better.

And then I go into denial!!!  Remember that old joke: There's this river in Egypt - De Nile...  I'm so there.  With the crocodiles.  I'm gonna randomly start crying next time I buy a pita wrap.  And the nice man behind the counter will say, "What's the matter, sweetheart?" and give me something sweet for free.  'Cause that dude totally rocks.  But I'm not actually going to cry.  I sort of keep smiling, albeit awkwardly.  I have these smile creases on my face, the result of a long long day.  And I don't feel well, I suppose because of my weird sleep schedule today.  And I didn't eat my dinner because I didn't feel well enough (never mind my stomach's growling) and gave my chicken sandwich to a hyper freshman, after she pretended to steal it.  I guess that's how you let people know what you want - pretend to try to steal it.  But that's just so wrong and the thought makes me curl my lip up and go, hnn.

Well, not with sandwiches.  That was perfectly okay.

But on a happier note, that chicken sandwich gave her the energy to paint an interesting achromatic work with nifty overlapping circles.  Like I said, today was a good day.  It still is a good day - the one negative thing (other than my not feeling well physically) doesn't cancel out any of that.  I simply feel that stifled feeling, where I want to be like, *EMOTIONS!!!* and then this guy is like, *Exactly!!!*

But on another happier note, I am no longer obsessed with Gibbs or his hair.  Do you hear me, Angelo?  No more trying to make me feel awkward in his presence!!!  That was a short lived quasi joke anyway.  Not to say that either Gibbs or his hair is joke fodder.  Gibbs and his hair and both very very cool, but I am not obsessed with either.  Take that.

*Owari*

Okay, so despite the worrying thing (and things are still pretty good, no actual cause for worry) today rocked my knee socks. Basically, cause I wore zebra print shorts and saw sooo many friends on a day when being alone was just not going to be cool.
I saw Joe Mc after my first class and he was all cute and nervous like he always is (apparently, he's just cute and nervous all the time!) and there was informative discussion and like ness. Joe is cool.
Then the super duper fun began at lunch. I was wandering around trying to find someone to eat with after my second class. Jamie was still MIA (in class) and so I headed across the dorm complex to find Justin and Angelo out front chattin' w/ ppl. Justin was starved too, so he and Angelo and their friend Ben and I went to Broooooower. Ew. I had a "hamburger." It didn't suck. And Justin swiped me in, so I was like yay! And he and (mostly) Angelo discussed how Pac Man is a metaphor for eating disorders and Justin was mildly violent toward him during that. I found it hilarious. Then it was the saga of RPG drama amongst the Demarites and Ben and I were like woah, totally weren't there. And Maria came over and I got to introduce her to 3 ppl who live in her building! And then she poofled off to her table. And while J & A were gazing into the magical machine that bestows espresso, Ben and I were becoming friends, which was fun. I love meeting Demarites cause they're just so used to talking with random ppl like me. And he gave me a marshmallow, but I don't think I like marshmallows anymore!!! The horror! But I still like the dehydrated kind, go fig.
So then Justin was off to his apt and A & B & I were like, let's go find people! But only after we did an experiment to find out whether or not my hypothesis about the position for a banana peel that will cause optimal slippage (but Ben didn't want to crack his head open so we had to do it on the grass, which I knew wouldn't work... duh.  But I may have to modify my hypothesis anyway because a folded banana peel does not rely on the smoothness of the surface... See, one peel section slips against the other when a moving weight, such as a foot, is placed upon it.  As there are always banana peels to be found, perhaps this will be tested as well). So then we discovered that people were at class. It woulda been fun to find someone like Noor, and be all like, Hi! We're the creative writing section that'll NEVER end! *hums that Lamp Chop song that for some reason, adults and "boring" people find annoying* Boring is in quotes because, like "normal," it's only been defined as what my friends and I don't get.
SO, no one was around and Angelo was like, I wish you were here when people were! But I had fun just looking for fun. Thanks, Angelo! And then Ben said he had to go to the museum to drop off his sched, so I said, hey, that's a fun thing! So I tagged along and we had a silly convo and I saw skeletons of Texan reptiles. But Ben doesn't think we (the reptiles and I) are related because I'm a mammal. I somehow think the Texan similarity overrides that, but I didn't bother trying to explain it. It's a thing where either you get it or you don't. And I'm not even sure I get it. 
So then Japanese with Dana and Mike. We may do something fun tomorrow involving Princeton. Just cause it's there! But now I have to plan it. Yay, planning things.
Oh, but other funny thing. The other day when I asked this random guy where to find Angelo, it turned out to be teh Ben. I didn't realize this until he made a reference to it. He was like, and I thought I was bad with faces! Heh heh, silly Audrey.
Later, I called Chris who met me at the student center and we caught up and had fun wondering what English majors are supposed to do upon graduation. ^_^ And he correctly analyzed me by saying that I want something great now (relationship wise) not just something nice in the meantime, which is what I tell myself I could go for. But Chris is smart and knows things and listens to me babble a lot. Maybe that's why I am never very interested in the nice guys I meet. And nice guys exist, which is awesome! I just don't fall head over heels. *shrugs* Maybe if I forget about wanting to date and just hang with guys I'll meet a dude I actually LIKE like, as they say on Hey Arnold. What a great show. Damn, I'm tired.
And THEN... dinner and fudge cake with Jamie and then back to her dorm where Liz made me crack up so hard. And then bus to that study abroad meeting which was quite informative, yup yup. Japan, here I come! Mebbe.
Ran into Annemarie (Annamarie?) from the lit mag, but she has class during meetings. Rawr.  She's so sweet and it would have been nice to have a returning member.  Oh well.  Lotsa ppl signed up and I can always do more recruiting if ppl don't come to the meeting.  But I know people will!  It'll be grood.
-*-Owari-*-

I affirm that the following events did actually occur today, and I approve this message.

So this morning at about 9:15, I arrived at Kinko's, the "place to go" for all your copying needs.  I walked in, feeling all happy about having completed the pages for my booklet, only to be ignored once I reached the counter - for about 2-3 full minutes.  There were 3-4 people about 20 feet away behind the counter, none of whom paid any attention to their pink clad customer (moi).  One guy (who was in his 30s or 40s, old enough to know how to behave better towards customers) said, "I'll be with you in a moment," and turned right back to his computer screen.  Apparently, they were having a few compy problems that just couldn't wait five minutes so the guy could come talk to me and take my booklet!  

A few minutes passed.  Then a woman came out of the office and walked along the back of the counter, saying, "Have you been helped?" to no one in particular.  The guy to my left said that he had been helped (he turned out to be the owner of the disk that was all messed up and apparently required the attention of every employee).  I said, "not yet," in a very polite tone, but the woman walked right past me to ask another customer if she needed help!  The customer said, "No, I'm just putting these pictures in order."  The Kinko's woman asked her a question and then, satisfied that no one needed her assistance (because of course, I don't actually exist), turned and walked past me again and back into the office.  I didn't say anything as she went by the second time because people who don't exist have trouble with things like speech.  No really, I just watched her with an "are you really that rude?" expression.  It did not faze her.  Should have.

So I slumped against the counter again and sighed (because assuming good posture had not made me any more real to that woman) and said to the owner of the messed up disk, "At least we have some good music."  He smiled and nodded.  The music was okay in that it had a good beat, some chords and didn't seem anything like rap.  Kinko's gets 2 points for that.  I resolved to stand there and rock out in my mind while I waited, thereby spending my quality time in the Astrodome instead of the extremely strange and boring real world.  Messed-up-disk guy suggested that perhaps the Kinko's people thought we were together.  It was a nice statement meant to absolve the Kinko's employees of any responsibility or brainpower.  I said, "Maybe," and shook my head.  

I went back to staring at the guy who seemed to know the most.  I assumed he knew the most because he kept walking from one monitor to another and suggesting things to the girl at one of the consoles.  Of course, as it didn't seem to be helping, my assumption was probably incorrect.  Anyway, he was the only person employed at what I was beginning to suspect was a 21 and over only establishment who had spoken to me.  It was tempting to call out something like, "Hi, I'm not going anywhere," or "The weather's lovely over here; perhaps you'd like to come and see."  But somehow I had the idea that such an outburst, however unbitchy I might keep it, could antagonize him into ignoring me further - because he, unlike me, knew that what he was doing was so much more important that doing his job correctly, and why should he have to take any attitude from a freakin' customer?  What was I doing standing there anyway??  But I'm only pretending to have read his mind.  The only thing I know for sure about his thought process is what he said: "I'll be with you in just one moment."  He glanced at the monitor.  "Or maybe five."  I looked at him with an expression of "the hell you think you're trying to pull?"  He tried again: "Well, maybe only three.  Or no, probably five."  I think I probably glared at the poor man, but I'm sure it did him no permanent damage.

Giving up on the idea of embarassing myself by informing the man of his lack of class and sense, I turned to God for a more polite, more zen solution.  Not two seconds later, "Power of Love" by Huey Lewis and the News began playing.  Please note that the baby booklet in my arms cited my current favorite song as "Power of Love."  Do also note that this hopefully would become an actual bound production was designed to be read by members of my choir.  I.e., I sing.  I turned to the seemingly perfectly content man with the disk problem and said, "If I start singing, there'll be no way they could ignore me."  He seemed to think there was a chance of it working, so when the chorus rolled around, I began singing at a moderate decibel (really, not loud; I didn't want to annoy anyone).  Soon after "don't need no credit card to ride this train" the man behind the counter hopped up and came to find out just what it was that I wanted, and in a perfectly nice manner.  It really would have been perfectly nice had he done exactly the same thing ten minutes earlier.  Yet I take this success as proof that while God does not physically kick assholes in the seat of their pants, he works in much more creative ways.

To sum things up, my booklet was not going to be ready when I had hoped it would be.  I head heard from one who had been in my exact position only a year ago that about 25 copies would only take an hour or two to whip up, and when the man, called Torino (which means "the bird's" in Japanese - yes, with the apostrophe), informed me that it could not be done any sooner than 6 pm, a good 8 and a half hours away, I kindly informed him of the rumor of good, quick service.  He concurred that it was logical to assume that it would only take about an hour because things like this usually only took that long.  However, "as you can see," they were having some problems, said the Italian man with the Japanese name.  I accepted that I would not be able to present my booklet when I wanted to and said I would be by to pick up the finished product the next day.

Pondering my options, I called a couple hours later, wondering if asking for the 6 o'clock pick up time would put me higher on the list (and in case of a freak accident where things began to work well and progress sped up), but the Asian guy who had completely ignored me while I was in-store (I didn't mention him before because it looked as if he might have been helping another person and so it wouldn't really have been fair to implicate him in the cause of this annoyance) told me that it was impossible because there were just so many projects in line ahead of me.  They were just "swamped this week."  So, the official due time is noon tomorrow.

Lord help them when I return.

School is finally starting.  It felt really good to get out and do something today, even if it was on 6 hrs of sleep.  I took a group of girls around on a tour and said things like "Get involved!" and "Visit your academic advisor" so many times that they probably wanted to shoot me.  Oh well.  They asked lots of questions and I think I was helpful.  I was often like, how do I answer this question... it'll be too complicated for someone who doesn't know the school well, or, now I know the answer is in this pamphlet, but this transfer student from India was like quick with answers.  I said, "why isn't she in charge?"  It was cool; a lot of the girls had a good idea of where things were.  This one chick seemed depressed and at the end and woudln't sit at the same table as us... she told Ashley (who's my advisee, yay!) that college is just like HS... oh my gosh wow no.  It's so much better!  Well, if she gives it half a chance and talks to people, she'll find out that it rocks and there aren't stupid cliques (oh wait, there are, fraternities, but who cares? Um, NO ONE but the people in them).  I totally couldn't remember everyone's name.  But that's okay, cause I have their emails.  Two girls lost their group and joined mine.  Then they saw theirs again, but stayed with my group.  I said, you can go or stay, whatever you want, and one of the gals in my group originally said, "here's funner!" and the new girls agreed.  W00t!  So yeah, I was really tired after that, but it was a good experience.  And uhm... oh yeah, a few girls wanna join the art and lit mag (which I got back up to plug after introducing myself... hey, if the other gals were gonna go on about stuff I had to have my 2 minutes for the magazine!  And our advisor is also the mag's advisor, so she mentioned it a couple times as an example of things they could get involved with, so yay!) and try out for the choir I'm in, yay yay!  I'm glad they're excited.
Oh, and I got to give a bus tour and use the mic... whahahah!  That was great.  And no one seemed frightened by my enthusiasm ("Okay, here's OMR, you must go there, they have cheeeeeeeeesecake.  Oh, and cute waiter boys!  Oh, but that guy who drunk called me works there, so be careful.)
Thankfully, I've only had one drunk calling experience, although Phil promises to give me another... haha.  But actually, that might be interesting.  Even tho' drinking is stupid.  I heard these girls in another group talking about end of senior year parties and all the kegs they went through and I just don't see the appeal.  I was considering making a "public service announcement" over the PA just as a joke, but I couldn' think of a light/funny way to do it so I didn't.   Oh well.  I so hope they're careful!  Anyway, yeah, I'm such a mom.  I told my group, "this intersection is really dangerous, so be careful.  Sorry to sound like your mom, but, like, look both ways and stuff."  Cause it's in the middle of campus and it really is crazy there.
Okay, this is freakin' long.  Summary: It was a grood day.  The End.

Okay, so another update, 'cause I feel like blathering. I have never wanted school to start so badly. Summer is fine, but I just feel like all these things are about to start happening, but won't until school does. And I'm feeling so impatient!!! I will try to busy myself with the things that I have been meaning to accomplish this summer, so I can feel super unburdened and happy when classes begin: -finish cleaning up the pile of last year's papers that's in front of my closet... it's relatively tiny now. I mostly just need to file the remaining papers away... gaah, doom of the packrat!\ -improve my bass playing. I am SO lazy about this. Basically, I need to do some scales every day. It won't take that long, I just need to sit down and play. -um, vacuum my room. Feathers are rampant. -get a hair trim. Top layer is getting bushy. Hm, should I cut the bangs again? I might. -get in touch with Jackie to plan the first lit mag meeting. So, do any of you like art or poetry or short stories (of those of you who go to my school, of course)??? Let me know!!! -do something else fun. Whatever J and Dana and Swappy wanna do for what will end up being my last actual day of summer vacation before I have to start being responsible (for schoolish things) again. -go over school songs again. I actually did that once this month - go me! That might be it. The list of things to do once school has begun is just HUGE tho'. For me, school actually begins a week early due to orientation training and such. Ohh, it will be fun. Activities fairs and singing with the gals again and fun fun silly willy. And then work... but I am determined to be excited about my school work. Oh yes. I really want to like it, so I will. And there is much potential for good classes this semester. I mean, unless my profs are terribly horrible, things should be fine. And if they are terrible, I'll just make friends in class so we can get together and be confused as a group, which is always better than being confused alone. Yay! Go school! Hermione is my role model like woah. Studying! Yes, I WANT to study! I don't know who I'm kidding. But I do have interesting classes, so maybe the loving studying thing will happen. I wish it would. Some people enjoy it. I wanna enjoy it. And maybe I won't start playing FF7. Just 'cause, it's a distraction and I have so much going on. We'll see. *** OH, and:

According to www.uniformstore.com/longerscrubpants.htm, a normal inseam is 30".  Mine is 29".  So I do not have ridiculously short hobbit legs.  If I did, I would understand why these pants that are SOO cute did not fit properly.
Of course, sizing is subjective, isn't it?  I should find a second source.

I don't think I need to go on and on about how ridiculously subjective women's clothing sizes are.  So, I will instead provide a simple solution: Size women's clothing the way men's clothing is sized!  Their pant sizing, with two numbers -one for waist, one for length, we all know how it works- makes SO much more sense than "this is what OUR size 4 is... and no, we don't offer smaller sizes.  At all.  Because what, are there women in existence who are shorter than that?"
Ew.  Clothing people suck.
According to their sizing chart, I should be a size 6.  But I knew better and ordered a 4.
And how many size 4 people are 5'10"?  Because that is how tall I would have to be for the jean "knickers" I ordered to fall at the appropriate length.  Right now they're long capris.  Do you know what that is?   It's FALSE ADVERTIZING.  That model is VERY tall.  Many people are not.  Give us the choice of long or short pants, okay?  Old Navy does it, Express does it (although ALL their pants are uber muchly low rise, but I won't get into that lack of judgement and common sense now), why can't Newport News do it?  *in a Scottish accent* Those bastards.  Discriminating against tiny people.  Maybe I should come back after I've had about three children.  Perhaps my hips will stretch the fabric and make the jeans shorter.  Um, no.  
And here is the most ridiculous thing: I don't even have short legs!!!  They're like, normal!!!
*rolls eyes*

...bringing up that plan of jamming that I suggested back when things were normal.
I guess they're normal again.  Only much more interesting. 
^_^
So, I love friends.  4 of my guy friends have been helping me sort thru this day after rejection thing.  It's great.  I really don't feel bad anymore.  Yay!
